:"Thorley, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wylley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Staffordshire, Cheshire, and Lancashire): variant of   Whaley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Whaley","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from Whalley (Lancashire) or Whaley in Bolsover (Derbyshire). The Lancashire placename may derive from Old English <i>hwæl</i> ‘hill’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, woodland clearing’. The Derbyshire placename may derive from Old English <i>wall</i> ‘wall’, <i>walh</i> ‘Welshman, foreigner’ (genitive plural <i>wala</i>), or <i>wælla</i> ‘well, spring, stream’ + <i>lēah</i>."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Wylley was born in 1375, in Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William De Wylly, was 79 and his mother, Mrs. William De Wylly, was 77. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Alice Wylley. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1375–":"1375–Surnud","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","1381–Female":"1381–Surnud","1400–1470":"1400–1470","1296–Male":"1296–Surnud","1298–Female":"1298–Surnud","1400":"1400","1375":"1375","1298":"1298","1296":"1296","1470":"1470","1381":"1381","Prior Marson, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Thorley, Bishops Stortford, Hertfordshire, England":"Thorley, Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1375–":"1375–Kuollut","1375–Male":"1375–Kuollut","1381–Female":"1381–Kuollut","1400–1470":"1400–1470","1296–Male":"1296–Kuollut","1298–Female":"1298–Kuollut","1400":"1400","1375":"1375","1298":"1298","1296":"1296","1470":"1470","1381":"1381","Prior Marson, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Thorley, Bishops Stortford, Hertfordshire, England":"Thorley, Hertfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1375–":"1375–Décédé","1375–Male":"1375–Décédé","1381–Female":"1381–Décédée","1400–1470":"1400–1470","1296–Male":"1296–Décédé","1298–Female":"1298–Décédée","1400":"1400","1375":"1375","1298":"1298","1296":"1296","1470":"1470","1381":"1381","Prior Marson, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Thorley, Bishops Stortford, Hertfordshire, England":"Thorley, Hertfordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Richard Wylley est né en 1375, à Warwickshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, William De Wylly, avait 79 ans et sa mère, Mrs. William De Wylly, avait 